200 members of the Philippine Movement for Climate Justice (PMCJ) staged a protest at the regional office of the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) in Tacloban city, Leyte on May 12 afternoon, against the government's environment policies and newly-appointed Environment Secretary Roy Cimatu.

Several thousand activists have marched in the Moroccan city of Marrakech to demand environmental justice, just a few kilometers (miles) away from where high-level U.N. climate change talks are being held. Native Americans protesting against the Dakota Access Pipeline demonstrated Sunday alongside local indigenous Amazigh groups protesting against a Moroccan companies expropriation of water resources, in addition to dozens of international civil society groups.

Moroccans burn an Israeli flag during a protest rally in the capital, Rabat, on November 9, 2016. Hundreds of people in Morocco have held a protest rally in the capital to vent their anger at the Israeli flag being flown at UN climate talks in the central city of Marrakesh.

assoc_actor_1: PMCJ: Philippine Movement for Climate Justice
notes: On 30 Aug 2016, in Manila, Metro Manila, around a dozen protesters led by Philippine Movement for Climate Justice (PMCJ) gathered outside the venue for a conference held by the Department of Energy (DOE) together with International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to oppose plans on reviving the development of atomic power in the country.
South African environmentalists, 350.org members and Right2Know activists converged in Johannesburg to demonstrate against climate change.

Several human rights activists and civil organisations today organised a candle light protest in support of Irom Chanu Sharmila who has been fasting for the last 16 years demanding repeal of the Armed Forces Special Powers Act. It was jointly organised by the North East Dialogue Forum, Conflict Widow Forum, Youth of Manipur, People's Platform Secretariat, Village Women Coordinating Committee, People for Human Rights and Climate Change, Environment Protection Network, Foundation Development Centre, Social Action Development Organisation, Social Youth Development Organisation, Social Welfare and Development Centre.

A mass rally was taken out today at the Chandel district headquarters demanding the immediate implementation of Manipur State Action Plan on Climate Change (MSAPCC). The rally was jointly organised by the Chandel District Farmers' Union (CDFU), Chakpi River Progressive and Development Society (CRPDS), Maha Area Chief Association Chandel (MACAC), Peoples' Development Organisation (PDO) and, Forest Natural Resources Management and Environment Development Council (FNRMEDC).
More than 1 000 Capetonians took to the streets as part of the global climate march on the eve of the COP21 climate talks that begin in Paris.
Hundreds of activists marched in Johannesburg urging their government to reduce its share of carbon emissions, ahead of the UN COP21 climate conference in Paris.

4,500 people took part in a run under the slogan 'Egypt fights climate change' in Zamalek. Organisers incorporated the run for climate change with Cairo Runners, due to difficulties of organising marches in Egypt.

Tens of thousands of people took to the streets of Tunis on Saturday to oppose globalization under the slogan 'another world is possible.' The demonstration was held as the 12th annual World Social Forum unfolded in the Tunisian capital. The demonstrators showed 'that global trade relations, migration policies and climate justice must adhere to democratic principles and the observation of human rights.'
Health workers affiliated with the Independent Union of Health protested against the 'bad social climate prevailing in their hospital'. They engaged in a sit-in at their hospital.
The opposition parties of the NCF boycotted the dialogue meeting which occurred on Sunday, and have announced they will boycott next years elections if the political climate does not improve.

notes: Agreement: Political parties across the spectrum sign a code of conduct to foster a climate of peace before, during and after the July 15 parliamentary and local elections of 2013. Document initiated by UNDP.
Environmental protest outside of a UN climate meeting in Durban. There were reported of escalated violence between two opposing political groups.
Climate change protest
Environmental activists gather on the campus of the University of KwaZula-Natal to call for 'climate justice.'
A group of environmentalists gather at the 17th Conference of the Parties of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change to protest elements of conference.
On Nov 15, Green Belt Trust formed a human chain on Dhaka University campus demanding climate justice and compensation for people affected by the adverse impact of climate change.
On Nov 13, several thousand people formed a human chain in Barisal city protesting rich nations' unwillingness to compensate the countries affected by climate change.
On Nov 13, Sushasoner Jonno Procharavijan (Supro) formed a human chain at Shahbagh in Dhaka demanding compensation from countries responsible for the adverse effects of climate change.

Hundreds of teachers marched on 17 May in Kherrata to denounce the climate of insecurity and violence prevailing in the vicinity of schools. This action comes days after the assault of the Director of EMC Taheyat-Ahmed of the same locality by a gang of 'thugs'.

Rioters, protesting the demolition of houses in Climate de France in Oued Koriche district of Algiers, clashed with police, leaving 21 police injured, one rioter injured and the death of seven month old baby girl dead, asphyxiated by the polices tear gas.

In Rutana specifically, the rebels are reinforcing the climate of fear by burning houses and pillaging households in the Nyamateke sector. The rebels set fire to four houses there and kidnapped one person.
